00:09:12.690 --> 00:09:14.500
at the Library of Congress
was the morning

00:09:14.500 --> 00:09:17.940
after Snowmageddon,
do you remember that?

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:21.120
And so I had a real
challenge getting here,

00:09:21.120 --> 00:09:22.420
getting down the streets.

00:09:22.420 --> 00:09:24.460
This time my challenge was
getting here not looking

00:09:24.460 --> 00:09:26.230
like I had been in a swimming pool.

00:09:26.230 --> 00:09:29.890
So I parked at Union
Station, took off my jacket

00:09:29.890 --> 00:09:33.070
and walked really slowly.

00:09:33.070 --> 00:09:37.220
It is doubly fun and a little
nerve-racking to speak here.

00:09:37.220 --> 00:09:40.180
The pleasure comes from the
fact that this institution has

00:09:40.180 --> 00:09:43.250
so lovingly cared for
Ethel Payne's papers.

00:09:43.250 --> 00:09:45.340
And if it weren't for the Library

00:09:45.340 --> 00:09:48.800
of Congress' care this book
couldn't have been written.

00:09:48.800 --> 00:09:51.380
The fear factor comes
when I speak in Washington

00:09:51.380 --> 00:09:54.570
and Chicago invariably there
are people who knew Ethel Payne

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:59.210
in the audience, so that
certainly puts me on my toes.

00:09:59.210 --> 00:10:02.750
I want to start the story
that I introduce you

00:10:02.750 --> 00:10:06.540
to Ethel Payne in February of 1954.

00:10:06.540 --> 00:10:08.470
Obviously, a significant year

00:10:08.470 --> 00:10:11.040
because in a few months Brown
v. Board is going to come

00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:13.370
down from the Supreme Court.

00:10:13.370 --> 00:10:17.240
But on that day Ethel
Payne is an angry soul.

00:10:17.240 --> 00:10:20.630
She's really furious and she's
on her way to this building,

00:10:20.630 --> 00:10:22.830
the old executive office building.

00:10:22.830 --> 00:10:26.430
And she particularly
wants to speak to this ma.

00:10:26.430 --> 00:10:29.180
Eisenhower had been in
the White House for a year

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:32.210
and Republicans were just so happy.

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:34.440
It was the first time
since the depression

00:10:34.440 --> 00:10:37.880
that a Republican inhabited the
White House and as you know,

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:40.700
control of the White House
means a lot of appointments,

00:10:40.700 --> 00:10:43.220
a resurgence for that
particular party.

00:10:43.220 --> 00:10:45.800
And so the Republicans were
gathering around the country

00:10:45.800 --> 00:10:48.140
for their Lincoln Day dinners.

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:51.460
Lincoln of course being a person of
central importance to Republicans

00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:54.890
when Lincoln's birthday comes
around from small courthouses

00:10:54.890 --> 00:10:57.980
in the Midwest to Washington DC
there are Lincoln Day gatherings

00:10:57.980 --> 00:10:59.280
like this.

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:03.950
And this one was held in the
old Uline not auditorium,

00:11:03.950 --> 00:11:08.210
but you know a building
the one that is long gone.

00:11:08.210 --> 00:11:11.970
And they'd invited three
choirs to come and perform.

00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:15.390
Two were from white private
universities in the south

00:11:15.390 --> 00:11:19.570
and the third choir was a
choir from Howard University.

00:11:19.570 --> 00:11:23.180
The choir from Howard University's
bus was banned and blocked

00:11:23.180 --> 00:11:25.900
from entering into the facility.

00:11:25.900 --> 00:11:28.230
Now I was born in Washington
and anyone

00:11:28.230 --> 00:11:31.740
who knew Washington back then
would've understood exactly why it

00:11:31.740 --> 00:11:33.040
was the case.

00:11:33.040 --> 00:11:35.520
The only group of black kids
approaching the building somehow

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:36.990
couldn't get in.

00:11:36.990 --> 00:11:39.240
So Ethel Payne was
furious about this.

00:11:39.240 --> 00:11:40.800
She was also furious about the fact

00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:43.780
that they had a black face
performance during this ceremony

00:11:43.780 --> 00:11:46.500
and she had already written
to the Republicans about this.

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:50.330
But now she wanted to come to one
of Eisenhower's press conferences

00:11:50.330 --> 00:11:51.700
to take it up with the man himself.

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:53.000
He had been the speaker,
he's the head

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.670
of the Republican Party what does
he have to say about what went

00:11:56.670 --> 00:12:00.060
on over the weekend at
the Lincoln Day event.

00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:04.040
And how did she get to do
that, how did she get to be

00:12:04.040 --> 00:12:06.450
in the White House press
corps to ask that question?

00:12:06.450 --> 00:12:09.000
Well Ethel Payne was then
the Washington correspondent

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.290
for the Chicago Defender,
the most widely circulated

00:12:12.290 --> 00:12:15.580
and significantly important
African-American newspaper

00:12:15.580 --> 00:12:16.880
at the time.

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:20.820
Now often when I give these
talks or interview people talk

00:12:20.820 --> 00:12:23.180
about whether I discovered
Ethel Payne.

00:12:23.180 --> 00:12:24.540
And it's an uncomfortable moment

00:12:24.540 --> 00:12:27.510
because Ethel Payne didn't
need any discovering.

00:12:27.510 --> 00:12:30.750
The truth of the matter is that
our segregation from that period

00:12:30.750 --> 00:12:33.460 position:56%
in a sense continues in our history.

00:12:33.460 --> 00:12:38.140 position:56%
That just like many African-American
institutions the black press

00:12:38.140 --> 00:12:41.820
operated in complete
invisibility to white America.

00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:45.280
But it's a story press it
goes all the way back to 1827

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:48.490
with the Freedom Journal of
the Baltimore Afro-American.

00:12:48.490 --> 00:12:51.820
Many of these papers that, you
know, valiantly crusaded not only

00:12:51.820 --> 00:12:56.200 position:56%
to end slavery, but to work
against Jim Crow to end segregation.

00:12:56.200 --> 00:12:59.940
And Ethel Payne had a particularly
lovely connection to the paper

00:12:59.940 --> 00:13:02.300
because her dad was
a Pullman porter.

00:13:02.300 --> 00:13:05.150
You're seeing a photograph
of Pullman porters.

00:13:05.150 --> 00:13:07.440
Well Pullman porters
played an interesting role

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:10.840 position:56%
in the life of the Chicago Defender.

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:13.570
If you're unfamiliar with the
Chicago Defender do not think of it

00:13:13.570 --> 00:13:16.610
as merely a Chicago newspaper
any more than we might think

00:13:16.610 --> 00:13:19.920
of the New York Times as
merely a New York paper.

00:13:19.920 --> 00:13:24.240 position:56%
Chicago Defender was circulated
nationally after it started in 1905,

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:26.240
but to get the Chicago Defender

00:13:26.240 --> 00:13:29.590
in some southern counties
was not only illegal

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:31.640
where there were actually
laws against reading

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:33.400
and circulating the
Chicago Defender.

00:13:33.400 --> 00:13:36.510
But more seriously it could
involve the loss of life.

00:13:36.510 --> 00:13:39.300
You did not want to be seen as
an African-American in the south

00:13:39.300 --> 00:13:42.470
with a copy of the Chicago Defender
sticking out your back pocket.

00:13:42.470 --> 00:13:46.220
So you were not going to
subscribe to it by mail.

00:13:46.220 --> 00:13:51.030
Yet Pullman porters who traveled
the nation would then take bundles,

00:13:51.030 --> 00:13:54.430
Chicago being the nerve center of
the rail system, would take bundles

00:13:54.430 --> 00:13:57.690
of the paper south with
them and leave them in towns

00:13:57.690 --> 00:14:00.230
and they would be set
up in the barbershops

00:14:00.230 --> 00:14:02.040
of the towns as a weekly then.

00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:04.490
So when the men came in to
have their Saturday shave

00:14:04.490 --> 00:14:06.460 position:56%
or haircut they could pick up a copy

00:14:06.460 --> 00:14:08.000
of the Defender and
take it back home.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And it was read by at least six or
seven different people after that.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.620
Well Ethel Payne's dad
was a Pullman porter.

00:14:14.620 --> 00:14:16.790
Now I don't know if he
carried the papers too,

00:14:16.790 --> 00:14:19.840
but I've often loved
that connection.

00:14:19.840 --> 00:14:22.730
But being a Pullman porter also
offered certain advantages.

00:14:22.730 --> 00:14:25.440
She and her dad and her
mom settled in a part

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:28.700
of Southside Chicago
called West Englewood.

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:31.710
West Englewood is different than
the rest of Southside Chicago.

00:14:31.710 --> 00:14:33.980
Here's a picture of
Ethel at her birth.

00:14:33.980 --> 00:14:39.210
And here's a picture of their
house and those people who are

00:14:39.210 --> 00:14:42.530
from Chicago in this audience now
I'm petrified because there's an H

00:14:42.530 --> 00:14:45.850
in the name of her street, but
it's pronounced Troop Street.

00:14:45.850 --> 00:14:49.990
What was significant is that
he could afford to buy a house.

00:14:49.990 --> 00:14:53.390
Very few African Americans
could buy houses at that point.

00:14:53.390 --> 00:14:57.610
Those Pullman porter jobs and post
office jobs were the best to have.

00:14:57.610 --> 00:15:01.420
But more significantly than owning
the house West Englewood was a very

00:15:01.420 --> 00:15:05.150
different community
in Southside Chicago.

00:15:05.150 --> 00:15:09.610
Payne described it as being an
island in a sea of whiteness,

00:15:09.610 --> 00:15:12.390
meaning that all the
neighborhoods on all four sides

00:15:12.390 --> 00:15:14.110
of West Englewood were white.

00:15:14.110 --> 00:15:17.710
The significance of that because
segregation Chicago was done

00:15:17.710 --> 00:15:21.370
through economic means, through
social means, but not by law.

00:15:21.370 --> 00:15:24.530
If you were in that school district
you could walk to the school,

00:15:24.530 --> 00:15:27.040
so she was in white
school districts.

00:15:27.040 --> 00:15:29.970
Now isn't that white schools
were necessarily better

00:15:29.970 --> 00:15:33.460
than black schools, although in
many cases that could be the case.

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:38.390 position:56%
But more significantly, she lived
next door to Lynn Bloom High School.

00:15:38.390 --> 00:15:41.310
Lynn Bloom High School
was the jewel in the crown

00:15:41.310 --> 00:15:43.770
of the white school
system in Chicago.

00:15:43.770 --> 00:15:47.000 position:56%
So it wasn't she was just going to
a white school she was getting to go

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.850
to the best high school in Chicago.

00:15:49.850 --> 00:15:53.200
And early on when I was doing
this research somebody had told me

00:15:53.200 --> 00:15:56.470
that Ethel Payne had had
Ernest Hemingway's teacher

00:15:56.470 --> 00:15:59.520
as an English teacher at
Lynn Bloom High School.

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:03.110
Now I'm trained as a journalist
and my editor always said to me,

00:16:03.110 --> 00:16:06.240
if your mother says she
loves you check it out.

00:16:06.240 --> 00:16:12.120 position:56%
So I operate from a position of, you
know, critical thinking or cynicism.

00:16:12.120 --> 00:16:15.410
Well, it turns out that
in fact was the case.

00:16:15.410 --> 00:16:18.260
But what was more significant
for me wasn't

00:16:18.260 --> 00:16:21.630
that I had now a great anecdote
is how did she get to be there.

00:16:21.630 --> 00:16:24.810
Why had she left Oak Park to
come and teach at Lynn Bloom?

00:16:24.810 --> 00:16:28.350
Because when Lynn Bloom was opened
right after the Chicago riots

00:16:28.350 --> 00:16:32.460
in 1919 it was simply
the best school to be in.

00:16:32.460 --> 00:16:36.020
So any teacher her
caliber which gladly move.

00:16:36.020 --> 00:16:37.320
And I use that because I want you

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:40.720
to understand how significant
getting to go to Lynn Bloom was.

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:42.020
It's a school that takes

00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:44.960
up an entire block it
looks like a college.

00:16:44.960 --> 00:16:47.500
Not only was it built in
such an important fashion,

00:16:47.500 --> 00:16:49.830
but it attracted the best teachers.

00:16:49.830 --> 00:16:51.900
Now a little moment of
social justice here.

00:16:51.900 --> 00:16:54.520
When Ethel Payne went to
Lynn Bloom she was allowed

00:16:54.520 --> 00:16:56.670
to write some articles
for the school paper,

00:16:56.670 --> 00:16:58.990
at least one that I know
of, maybe some more.

00:16:58.990 --> 00:17:02.410
But she made it clear that just
even the thought of asking to be

00:17:02.410 --> 00:17:03.980
on the staff of this school

00:17:03.980 --> 00:17:08.230
which was 99.9% white
was out of the question.

00:17:08.230 --> 00:17:10.860
So her journalistic achievements
there were never recognized.

00:17:10.860 --> 00:17:14.830
Well I was invited to come
to Lynn Bloom and speak

00:17:14.830 --> 00:17:18.160
and the journalism room has now
been renamed the Ethel Payne

00:17:18.160 --> 00:17:20.030
Journalism Center.

00:17:20.030 --> 00:17:23.470
And I love the idea of succeeding
generations of kids coming

00:17:23.470 --> 00:17:25.090
in with their smart
phones and saying,

00:17:25.090 --> 00:17:28.720
who's this Payne fellow assuming
it's a guy looking her up

00:17:28.720 --> 00:17:31.380
and discovering who she
is and thus being inspired

00:17:31.380 --> 00:17:34.660
to perhaps do the same kind
of journey that she did.

00:17:34.660 --> 00:17:37.580
That's her graduating
from high school.

00:17:37.580 --> 00:17:39.140
When she graduated from
high school she went

00:17:39.140 --> 00:17:41.390
on to get some various
forms of education.

00:17:41.390 --> 00:17:43.190 position:56%
She went to Crane Community College,

00:17:43.190 --> 00:17:45.360
which is now Malcolm
X Community College.

00:17:45.360 --> 00:17:47.100
She went to Garrett, which was --

00:17:47.100 --> 00:17:51.070
it actually had a long name then
it was called the Mission School

00:17:51.070 --> 00:17:54.240
for Social Training and
something else and rather.

00:17:54.240 --> 00:17:57.530
It was a religiously-based free
college that was opened to blacks

00:17:57.530 --> 00:18:01.590 position:56%
and whites to basically teach you to
be a social worker or a missionary.

00:18:01.590 --> 00:18:05.580
She used that training to work in
a corrections facility for a while,

00:18:05.580 --> 00:18:07.480
but she couldn't get work.

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:09.550
She couldn't get the
work that she wanted.

00:18:09.550 --> 00:18:14.450 position:56%
She did publish in Abbott's Monthly
which was the premier black magazine

00:18:14.450 --> 00:18:18.020
of the time in which Richard Wright
published his first short story

00:18:18.020 --> 00:18:20.400
at the same time Ethel Payne
was publishing her friction,

00:18:20.400 --> 00:18:22.290
a remarkable achievement.

00:18:22.290 --> 00:18:25.300
But to get a professional
job, particularly one

00:18:25.300 --> 00:18:27.810
that involved writing
in Chicago was as rare

00:18:27.810 --> 00:18:30.500
as a warm day in winter
in that city.

00:18:30.500 --> 00:18:33.090
Seven out of 10 African-American
women according

00:18:33.090 --> 00:18:36.050
to a labor census I found
who had a job in Chicago

00:18:36.050 --> 00:18:39.430
at that time worked
as domestic servants.

00:18:39.430 --> 00:18:43.350
So Payne looked quite
far away for a job.

00:18:43.350 --> 00:18:49.390
She had heard that they
needed service club employees

00:18:49.390 --> 00:18:52.770
in occupied Japan in 1948.

00:18:52.770 --> 00:18:55.960
Now if you remember it's like
USO there were these clubs all

00:18:55.960 --> 00:18:58.160
around the world for troops.

00:18:58.160 --> 00:18:59.810
And you're going to say 1948.

00:18:59.810 --> 00:19:04.440
Of course, Truman has desegregated
the military through his order.

00:19:04.440 --> 00:19:08.460
Well, there was this General
MacArthur in Japan who had a habit

00:19:08.460 --> 00:19:11.600
of never listening to his
president, his commander-in-chief.

00:19:11.600 --> 00:19:13.340
As you know, that ends up one

00:19:13.340 --> 00:19:15.070
of the reasons he didn't
get to keep his job.

00:19:15.070 --> 00:19:19.450
So he had no intention of
disaggregating the troops.

00:19:19.450 --> 00:19:21.900
And if I remember I'll tell
you a funny story I found

00:19:21.900 --> 00:19:23.200
in your archives about it.

00:19:23.200 --> 00:19:27.700
But Ethel Payne got a job then as a
service club hostess to go to Japan

00:19:27.700 --> 00:19:30.490
and leave Chicago and
work in a service club.

00:19:30.490 --> 00:19:32.440
Now this is an extraordinary
journey,

00:19:32.440 --> 00:19:35.620
I mean she's leaving
Southside Chicago to go halfway

00:19:35.620 --> 00:19:37.460
around the world to
work with troops.

00:19:37.460 --> 00:19:40.780
There's a photograph of her with
a group of young black troops

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:45.470
about to go into Tokyo and here
she is organizing a birthday party.

00:19:45.470 --> 00:19:48.920
So many things happened to her
and the other soldiers there.

00:19:48.920 --> 00:19:51.830
For many of them it was the
first time to live in a society

00:19:51.830 --> 00:19:54.760
without the kinds of
segregations they had at home.

00:19:54.760 --> 00:19:56.780
One and I won't quote
it exactly right,

00:19:56.780 --> 00:19:58.080
but it's in my book right here.

00:19:58.080 --> 00:20:02.940 position:56%
But one soldier wrote back and said,
you know, I'm not a Negro here.

00:20:02.940 --> 00:20:06.830
Now the Japanese are xenophobic and
they're not wild about foreigners,

00:20:06.830 --> 00:20:08.750
but they didn't have
the kind of racism

00:20:08.750 --> 00:20:10.870
that the southern troop
leaders certainly did.

00:20:10.870 --> 00:20:13.180 position:56%
So as soon as they left the confines

00:20:13.180 --> 00:20:17.330 position:56%
of their base they experienced a
kind of life that was very different

00:20:17.330 --> 00:20:19.340
and it changed a lot
of their viewpoint

00:20:19.340 --> 00:20:20.970
of the United States
when they came back.

00:20:20.970 --> 00:20:24.070
But one of the things Ethel Payne
observed while she was there

00:20:24.070 --> 00:20:28.700
in the destitute days of Japan's
occupancy was that a lot --

00:20:28.700 --> 00:20:33.120
there were a lot of single Japanese
women either widows or young women.

00:20:33.120 --> 00:20:37.300
And remember it's a very destitute
country who were quite eager

00:20:37.300 --> 00:20:40.920
to enjoy the economic might
that the young American white

00:20:40.920 --> 00:20:43.090
and black soldiers had.

00:20:43.090 --> 00:20:46.350
And so they dated quite
freely the American troops.

00:20:46.350 --> 00:20:49.870
Well black soldiers also
dated Japanese women.

00:20:49.870 --> 00:20:55.080
This created a whole new
problem because it created

00:20:55.080 --> 00:20:57.360
like as you know the
result of dating often

00:20:57.360 --> 00:20:58.660
in those periods were children.

00:20:58.660 --> 00:21:01.340
And these mixed-race orphans,

00:21:01.340 --> 00:21:03.850
I mean these mixed-race
children became orphans

00:21:03.850 --> 00:21:06.160
because the Japanese
women rejected them

00:21:06.160 --> 00:21:08.610
because they were partially
African-American,

00:21:08.610 --> 00:21:12.830
sometimes actually engaged in
infanticide or just abandoned them

00:21:12.830 --> 00:21:14.990
and they ended up in an orphanage.

00:21:14.990 --> 00:21:18.440
From the point of view of the
military this was another horror

00:21:18.440 --> 00:21:21.210
because remember most of
the military command come

00:21:21.210 --> 00:21:24.910
from southern states where the
idea of any form of communication

00:21:24.910 --> 00:21:28.280
between an African-American
and a woman outside

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:32.590
of the African-American
race was a crime.

00:21:32.590 --> 00:21:37.050
And so they viewed Japanese women
almost in the sense as being white

00:21:37.050 --> 00:21:38.370
and having this relationship.

00:21:38.370 --> 00:21:41.830
So these poor children were
completely abandoned and ignored.

00:21:41.830 --> 00:21:44.790
And Ethel Payne took a
great interest in writing

00:21:44.790 --> 00:21:46.560
about them and learning about them.

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:48.590
She'd taken an interest
in everything in Japan,

00:21:48.590 --> 00:21:50.330
but she had no place to publish it.

00:21:50.330 --> 00:21:51.630
So in a sense I like to think

00:21:51.630 --> 00:21:53.990
that her diary became
her place of publication.

00:21:53.990 --> 00:21:57.360
She went to see the war
tribunals, she wrote about it.

00:21:57.360 --> 00:22:00.660
She went to learn about these
poor orphans and wrote about it.

00:22:00.660 --> 00:22:05.330
Well the Korean War broke out
and the only way you could get

00:22:05.330 --> 00:22:07.720
to the Korean War as a reporter
was to come through Japan,

00:22:07.720 --> 00:22:09.330
that's where the central
headquarters were.

00:22:09.330 --> 00:22:11.320
So Alex Wilson of the
Chicago Defender,

00:22:11.320 --> 00:22:15.120
James Hicks from the Baltimore
Afro-American came to write.

00:22:15.120 --> 00:22:18.420
Because remember the troops
are segregated so their conduct

00:22:18.420 --> 00:22:20.690
in the war is a big story
for black newspapers

00:22:20.690 --> 00:22:22.490
in the United states
virtually ignored

00:22:22.490 --> 00:22:24.440
by the white papers in the states.

00:22:24.440 --> 00:22:27.110
And they were facing
some unusual problems

00:22:27.110 --> 00:22:30.050
since the black troops
couldn't be relieved

00:22:30.050 --> 00:22:34.080
by white soldiers they
weren't getting relieved

00:22:34.080 --> 00:22:35.860 position:56%
at the same rate on the front lines.

00:22:35.860 --> 00:22:39.240
And if you remember your history of
the Korean War it's not going well

00:22:39.240 --> 00:22:40.760
for the first few months.

00:22:40.760 --> 00:22:44.300
And so and let's not forget
these are kids essentially 18

00:22:44.300 --> 00:22:48.570
19-year-olds, kids facing the
barrels of North Korean rifles.

00:22:48.570 --> 00:22:50.580
So a lot of them fled
the front lines.

00:22:50.580 --> 00:22:53.250
They were, I shouldn't say
lines, but a fair number.

00:22:53.250 --> 00:22:55.730
And they were immediately
court-martialed with a potential

00:22:55.730 --> 00:22:58.100 position:56%
of being executed for their actions.

00:22:58.100 --> 00:23:02.300
Thurgood Marshall came
to defend them,

00:23:02.300 --> 00:23:04.570
he was then a young
lawyer with the NAACP.

00:23:04.570 --> 00:23:06.970
It took him two tries
to win permission

00:23:06.970 --> 00:23:08.900
from General MacArthur to come.

00:23:08.900 --> 00:23:11.970
And here's the little story,
it's in an endnote inside my book

00:23:11.970 --> 00:23:14.080 position:56%
if you want to get it completely
right because I'll probably screw it

00:23:14.080 --> 00:23:17.140
up a little bit, but I found it
downstairs in the manuscript room.

00:23:17.140 --> 00:23:20.400
He's having a conversation with
MacArthur outside of his building

00:23:20.400 --> 00:23:24.660
and it's one of these typical
black-and-white power discussions

00:23:24.660 --> 00:23:30.240
of that time where Marshall
says something like, you know,

00:23:30.240 --> 00:23:33.670
there's this black soldier who's
killed more people as a sniper

00:23:33.670 --> 00:23:36.550
than any white soldier now
why he can't he be doing this.

00:23:36.550 --> 00:23:39.390
And there's a soldier who
has this, you know going

00:23:39.390 --> 00:23:40.990
through the whole list
and McArthur kept saying,

00:23:40.990 --> 00:23:42.470
no I can't find anyone
that's good enough.

00:23:42.470 --> 00:23:44.790
What about this and no, I can't
find anyone that's good enough.

00:23:44.790 --> 00:23:48.280
And the band comes out, it's
all white and McArthur says,

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:51.010
God I just love the
music of that band.

00:23:51.010 --> 00:23:53.410
And I wish I had it in front of you
because I won't get it quite right.

00:23:53.410 --> 00:23:55.650
Marshall turns to him and says,
now you're not going to say

00:23:55.650 --> 00:23:57.820
to me Mr. General that
you couldn't find a Negro

00:23:57.820 --> 00:24:00.970
who could blow a horn
as well as these guys.

00:24:00.970 --> 00:24:03.810
I couldn't get it in the
book, but my editor allowed me

00:24:03.810 --> 00:24:06.090
to sneak it into the end notes.

00:24:06.090 --> 00:24:09.120
So Ethel Payne this is
her upon return to Chicago

00:24:09.120 --> 00:24:12.570
at one point wearing
her Japanese clothes.

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:16.530
She meets with Alec Wilson and
James Hicks, these reporters

00:24:16.530 --> 00:24:20.710 position:56%
at the press club in Japan and
tells them about this fraternization

00:24:20.710 --> 00:24:25.390
between the soldiers and these poor
orphans that have been stranded.

00:24:25.390 --> 00:24:28.500
And Alex Wilson says,
can I borrow your diary

00:24:28.500 --> 00:24:31.720
and as a result the Chicago
Defender publishes the first

00:24:31.720 --> 00:24:33.840 position:56%
of two byline pieces by Ethel Payne.

00:24:33.840 --> 00:24:37.860
It says, Japan girls playing
GIs for sucker says fate

00:24:37.860 --> 00:24:41.730
that awaits war babies is
tragedy of yank Oriental unions.

00:24:41.730 --> 00:24:45.400
Jet Magazine gets into it with
a photograph of these poor kids

00:24:45.400 --> 00:24:47.860
who are being taunted by other kids

00:24:47.860 --> 00:24:51.350
and being called half-breed
Americans.

00:24:51.350 --> 00:24:54.070
Well the story was a
sensation back home.

00:24:54.070 --> 00:24:57.950
Her sister placed a cross
specific call to her saying,

00:24:57.950 --> 00:25:01.150
do you realize you're on the
front page of the Defender.

00:25:01.150 --> 00:25:02.860
It also got her into
a lot of trouble

00:25:02.860 --> 00:25:04.780
because as you can
imagine the central command

00:25:04.780 --> 00:25:07.570
in Japan was not happy
with this kind of coverage.

00:25:07.570 --> 00:25:11.270
So they yanked her from her job,
they put her a dead-end desk job

00:25:11.270 --> 00:25:13.180
and MacArthur before he left Japan

00:25:13.180 --> 00:25:15.590
after defending their soldiers
got her out of trouble.

00:25:15.590 --> 00:25:20.290
Well the Defender true to its
word having got her deeply

00:25:20.290 --> 00:25:23.830
into trouble offered her a job
and she headed back to Chicago

00:25:23.830 --> 00:25:25.440
to work for the Defender.

00:25:25.440 --> 00:25:29.060 position:56%
Now let's not think that the
Defender is being merely charitable.

00:25:29.060 --> 00:25:32.660
Louis Martin, the editor,
and others there clearly knew

00:25:32.660 --> 00:25:34.550
that Ethel Payne was a journalist.

00:25:34.550 --> 00:25:39.000
She had a keen eye for stories
what she didn't have was training.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.750
She'd taken a couple courses
on writing at [inaudible],

00:25:41.750 --> 00:25:44.190
but she was not trained
as a journalist.

00:25:44.190 --> 00:25:47.500
And I was on a radio show one
day and the host said something.

00:25:47.500 --> 00:25:49.360
I wish he had told me this
before I had written the book

00:25:49.360 --> 00:25:50.700
because I would have put it in it.

00:25:50.700 --> 00:25:53.650
He said that reading her
struck him that she was much

00:25:53.650 --> 00:25:56.700
like a jazz artist,
learning in the band

00:25:56.700 --> 00:25:59.300
and in the playing,
but not in the schools.

00:25:59.300 --> 00:26:03.180
So she came back to Chicago,
worked for the Chicago Defender.

00:26:03.180 --> 00:26:07.060 position:56%
Here's a picture of her with Adlai
Stevenson, the governor of Illinois,

00:26:07.060 --> 00:26:10.290
two times candidate for
President of the United States.

00:26:10.290 --> 00:26:12.810
I assume you all know
quip about why he lost.

00:26:12.810 --> 00:26:16.730
Somebody said to him once you're
the thinking man's candidate

00:26:16.730 --> 00:26:18.030
for president.

00:26:18.030 --> 00:26:21.090
He said yes that was the problem.

00:26:21.090 --> 00:26:24.100
And she's really doing well,

00:26:24.100 --> 00:26:26.440
she's writing terrific
coverage in Chicago.

00:26:26.440 --> 00:26:28.330
She attracts the attention
of other papers.

00:26:28.330 --> 00:26:32.080
One paper offers her part
ownership of the paper

00:26:32.080 --> 00:26:33.820
if she would come to work for them.

00:26:33.820 --> 00:26:35.810
She gets ready to go
and Louis Martin says,

00:26:35.810 --> 00:26:41.470
