00:27:31.640 --> 00:27:32.940
to get in.

00:27:32.940 --> 00:27:34.740
Now you don't become president
without being somewhat smart.

00:27:34.740 --> 00:27:37.980
So Eisenhower says, well
if they were in fact barred

00:27:37.980 --> 00:27:41.570
because of race I apologize all
I'll have my people look into it.

00:27:41.570 --> 00:27:42.870
So he got out of that one.

00:27:42.870 --> 00:27:47.190 position:56%
But what Ethel Payne noticed is that
the next day the Washington Post,

00:27:47.190 --> 00:27:51.720
the local paper which prides itself
on covering news of the locality,

00:27:51.720 --> 00:27:55.480
had failed to cover that
story now wrote about it

00:27:55.480 --> 00:27:58.800
because it had been mentioned at
a presidential press conference.

00:27:58.800 --> 00:28:00.800
In other words, bringing up topics

00:28:00.800 --> 00:28:02.150
at the presidential
press conference,

00:28:02.150 --> 00:28:05.330
which had 197 white
reporters, 3 black reporters.

00:28:05.330 --> 00:28:07.810
If you brought up topics of
interest and civil rights

00:28:07.810 --> 00:28:12.090
or race matters it forced the other
reporters to have to cover it.

00:28:12.090 --> 00:28:14.800
Now it wasn't necessarily that
these reporters were racist

00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:17.690
as Ethel Payne would simply say,
some were but most of them weren't,

00:28:17.690 --> 00:28:21.350
it just wasn't part of
their daily experience.

00:28:21.350 --> 00:28:23.440
When Ethel Payne got up
to get to the White House,

00:28:23.440 --> 00:28:25.260
getting to the White
House was a challenge.

00:28:25.260 --> 00:28:29.000
Finding a bathroom she could use in
Washington in 1954 was a challenge.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:32.780 position:56%
Finding a place to eat was a
challenge not for the white reports.

00:28:32.780 --> 00:28:36.140
In a sense she felt that she was
part of the problem every day.

00:28:36.140 --> 00:28:40.080
She used the word problem, that's
a 1950's word for that issue.

00:28:40.080 --> 00:28:44.780
So she in a sense dropped
this notion of being objective

00:28:44.780 --> 00:28:47.330
and instead decided to be fair.

00:28:47.330 --> 00:28:52.250
But working with Louis
Martin, the Washington lobbyist

00:28:52.250 --> 00:28:54.860
for the NAACP nicknamed
the 101st senator

00:28:54.860 --> 00:28:56.610
because of his effectiveness.

00:28:56.610 --> 00:29:00.890
Every few weeks they would work
on crafting really good questions

00:29:00.890 --> 00:29:04.620 position:56%
and the questions weren't simply to
elicit from the president a response

00:29:04.620 --> 00:29:08.240 position:56%
on an important policy stance
regarding civil rights whether it be

00:29:08.240 --> 00:29:11.840
housing, busing or
federal money or jobs.

00:29:11.840 --> 00:29:14.790
But also to educate the
president and the press corps

00:29:14.790 --> 00:29:16.550
because they didn't
know about these issues.

00:29:16.550 --> 00:29:21.720
So when she would ask a question
sometimes the questions were really

00:29:21.720 --> 00:29:25.730
long out of necessity because
the guy up front didn't,

00:29:25.730 --> 00:29:27.730
I mean you know today you
get a [inaudible] together

00:29:27.730 --> 00:29:30.490
and they immediately start talking
shop because they know everything.

00:29:30.490 --> 00:29:32.530
Section eight housing,
all these terminologies,

00:29:32.530 --> 00:29:33.920
what are you doing
about the other thing.

00:29:33.920 --> 00:29:36.060
But Eisenhower knew nothing
about these civil rights issues

00:29:36.060 --> 00:29:37.360
and nor did the press corps.

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:40.280
So she continued to ask
these questions until one day

00:29:40.280 --> 00:29:45.720
in 1955 she said to him,
Mr. President you know

00:29:45.720 --> 00:29:48.260
under the commerce clause
of the constitution,

00:29:48.260 --> 00:29:51.240
again I'm paraphrasing you'll
find the exact words in the book,

00:29:51.240 --> 00:29:54.130
congress could desegregate
interstate bus travel.

00:29:54.130 --> 00:29:56.420
Are you in favor of doing
something like that,

00:29:56.420 --> 00:29:58.330
we really need your support?

00:29:58.330 --> 00:30:03.000
Well he rears up in his sort of
military posture and he says,

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:07.190
I don't know where you get
off asking that question.

00:30:07.190 --> 00:30:09.360
And you're thinking oh James
he's just getting excited

00:30:09.360 --> 00:30:11.350
up here having a chance
to talk to people

00:30:11.350 --> 00:30:15.110
and I'm exaggerating the
you could do what I did.

00:30:15.110 --> 00:30:17.250
But there's an even better
option I drove to Abilene,

00:30:17.250 --> 00:30:19.140
Kansas to hear the audio tape

00:30:19.140 --> 00:30:23.020
and you can hear his anger,
the timbre of his voice.

00:30:23.020 --> 00:30:25.400
He is clearly ticked
off at the effrontery

00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:27.090
of her to ask this question.

00:30:27.090 --> 00:30:28.900
Now if you want you
can just go to NPR

00:30:28.900 --> 00:30:32.020
because Karen Grigsby
Bates has the audio tape

00:30:32.020 --> 00:30:33.320
on a story about Ethel Payne.

00:30:33.320 --> 00:30:36.940
You can hear him going where do
you get off asking this question.

00:30:36.940 --> 00:30:40.990 position:56%
And then he goes on to say, you
know, I'm president of all Americans

00:30:40.990 --> 00:30:42.930
and I want to do what's in the best

00:30:42.930 --> 00:30:47.260
of all Americans not any just
little special interest group.

00:30:47.260 --> 00:30:49.020
The room went dead quiet.

00:30:49.020 --> 00:30:52.820
Eisenhower had said on the record
before the nation that the quest

00:30:52.820 --> 00:30:55.800
for equality by a large group
of Americans was tantamount

00:30:55.800 --> 00:30:58.800
to a special interest lobby
like let's say the farm lobby.

00:30:58.800 --> 00:31:02.550
A reporter quickly says, Mr.
President let's talk about Hawaii,

00:31:02.550 --> 00:31:04.270
you know, really uncomfortable.

00:31:04.270 --> 00:31:06.060
The next day of course,
there were headlines

00:31:06.060 --> 00:31:09.000
across the country a
reporter irks Ike, you know,

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:13.180
the old days when they had
that wonderful literation.

00:31:13.180 --> 00:31:16.670
And so Eisenhower learned
his lesson that day

00:31:16.670 --> 00:31:20.150
and the lesson was you don't
call on Ethel Payne anymore.

00:31:20.150 --> 00:31:21.970
So she was basically frozen out.

00:31:21.970 --> 00:31:24.690
Alice Dunnigan had the same
treatment over time too,

00:31:24.690 --> 00:31:26.730
her questions ceased to be asked.

00:31:26.730 --> 00:31:29.230
And we might not have heard much
more about Ethel Payne except

00:31:29.230 --> 00:31:33.240
for this woman who then as we
might have[inaudible] said,

00:31:33.240 --> 00:31:35.240
sat in the wrong part of the bus

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:39.110
and triggered the Montgomery
bus boycott at the same time.

00:31:39.110 --> 00:31:42.360
So Ethel Payne left Washington
and went to the front lines

00:31:42.360 --> 00:31:46.630
of the civil rights movement
in Montgomery and in Alabama,

00:31:46.630 --> 00:31:49.890
much to the consternation of her
paper who were quite unwilling

00:31:49.890 --> 00:31:52.310
to send her south until
this had happened.

00:31:52.310 --> 00:31:53.610
Why was that?

00:31:53.610 --> 00:31:54.910
Well let's think this through.

00:31:54.910 --> 00:31:58.600
She's black and she's female,
the two most expendable forms

00:31:58.600 --> 00:32:01.620
of life among white
segregationists in the south.

00:32:01.620 --> 00:32:06.270
But she carries something even more
fearful to them a reporter's pad.

00:32:06.270 --> 00:32:08.970
She was going to go south
and report to northern folks,

00:32:08.970 --> 00:32:11.530
particularly Afro-Americans
what was going on.

00:32:11.530 --> 00:32:13.670
So she arrives in Montgomery

00:32:13.670 --> 00:32:16.540
where these two men are
basically introducing themselves

00:32:16.540 --> 00:32:21.870 position:56%
to the nation, Martin Luther King,
Ralph Abernathy you see in the back.

00:32:21.870 --> 00:32:26.530
And she's just landed in
Montgomery and she does something

00:32:26.530 --> 00:32:30.060
that I think is incredible, I mean
having studied journalism history,

00:32:30.060 --> 00:32:33.280 position:56%
incredibly important and overlooked.

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:36.940
Which is now as a white guy writing
civil rights history 60 years later

00:32:36.940 --> 00:32:39.740
I can tell you the turning
moments, the turning points.

00:32:39.740 --> 00:32:42.150
But no one knew how
significant Montgomery was

00:32:42.150 --> 00:32:44.540
at that moment the
boycott had just begun.

00:32:44.540 --> 00:32:48.870
And more importantly, no one knew
yet about the extraordinary shift

00:32:48.870 --> 00:32:51.360
in the leadership of the
civil rights movement.

00:32:51.360 --> 00:32:54.650
Prior to that moment if you go back
to the 19th century you had people

00:32:54.650 --> 00:32:57.830
like Frederick Douglass or then
labor leaders like W. D. Boyce,

00:32:57.830 --> 00:33:00.480
you had the movement into
the legal arena with people

00:33:00.480 --> 00:33:03.490
like Thurgood Marshall,
the NAACP or the March

00:33:03.490 --> 00:33:06.090
on Washington movement
led by A. Philip Randolph.

00:33:06.090 --> 00:33:09.040
By the way, for whom she worked
with on the original March

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:13.780
on Washington before she became
a reporter in 1940 and 41.

00:33:13.780 --> 00:33:18.030
But now it was shifting to the
clergy and it was the birth

00:33:18.030 --> 00:33:19.890
of the nonviolent movement.

00:33:19.890 --> 00:33:22.530
And so she writes this sentence
her first week in Montgomery

00:33:22.530 --> 00:33:25.140
and she says, this
new gladiator goes

00:33:25.140 --> 00:33:29.170
into battle wearing a reverse
collar and holding a Bible.

00:33:29.170 --> 00:33:32.170
This new Moses is the
Negro preacher.

00:33:32.170 --> 00:33:33.800 position:56%
Now two things to notice about that.

00:33:33.800 --> 00:33:37.330
She's the first to perceive this
from the ground floor as opposed

00:33:37.330 --> 00:33:39.910
to the luxury of a
history book years later.

00:33:39.910 --> 00:33:42.240
But notice her language
and this is one

00:33:42.240 --> 00:33:45.790
of the reasons why Ethel Payne
is not necessarily remembered.

00:33:45.790 --> 00:33:48.500
We look at history
anachronistically,

00:33:48.500 --> 00:33:50.410
we look at it from the
viewpoint of today.

00:33:50.410 --> 00:33:54.350
So when the Library of America
assembled its two volumes,

00:33:54.350 --> 00:33:57.360
a collection of civil
rights reporting,

00:33:57.360 --> 00:33:59.520
Ethel Payne's not in
that collection.

00:33:59.520 --> 00:34:02.240
And why is that, because
historians looking back today,

00:34:02.240 --> 00:34:03.700
primarily white historians,

00:34:03.700 --> 00:34:07.290 position:56%
are looking for these great analytic
pieces written at enormous length

00:34:07.290 --> 00:34:10.040
with convoluted sentences and
analysis that might have appeared

00:34:10.040 --> 00:34:12.340
in say the New York Times.

00:34:12.340 --> 00:34:16.830 position:56%
They dismissed Ethel Payne because
they forget who she was writing for.

00:34:16.830 --> 00:34:20.210
She was writing for an audience
that when the paper started 50%

00:34:20.210 --> 00:34:22.670
of its potential readership
could not read.

00:34:22.670 --> 00:34:26.920
By the 1950's African-American
literacy rates had risen,

00:34:26.920 --> 00:34:30.010
but nonetheless she was going to
write for her audience no different

00:34:30.010 --> 00:34:33.670
than Jimmy Breslin in the Post
or Ernie Pyle in World War 2,

00:34:33.670 --> 00:34:34.970
you write for your audience.

00:34:34.970 --> 00:34:37.710
So she makes these
religious allusions coming

00:34:37.710 --> 00:34:40.220
out of St. John's AME
Church and she writes

00:34:40.220 --> 00:34:43.110 position:56%
in a particular style and it worked.

00:34:43.110 --> 00:34:45.970
She became this conduit
between the front lines

00:34:45.970 --> 00:34:48.590
of the civil rights movement
and black readership all

00:34:48.590 --> 00:34:52.610
around the United States serving
to activate, as well as to inform.

00:34:52.610 --> 00:34:53.910
Because one of the things

00:34:53.910 --> 00:34:58.200
about journalism is merely
reporting can trigger activation.

00:34:58.200 --> 00:34:59.630
Think about it, one
of the great powers

00:34:59.630 --> 00:35:02.880
of reporting is illuminating
the dark recesses in society,

00:35:02.880 --> 00:35:05.570
telling people about poverty,
telling people about things

00:35:05.570 --> 00:35:07.610
and that often triggers things.

00:35:07.610 --> 00:35:09.310
So there she was doing this,

00:35:09.310 --> 00:35:12.740
but I want to tell you another
anecdote that I just love.

00:35:12.740 --> 00:35:15.060
White reporters began to
show up in Montgomery,

00:35:15.060 --> 00:35:16.960
it was a big story right.

00:35:16.960 --> 00:35:20.680 position:56%
So they go to these church
meetings and when Martin Luther King

00:35:20.680 --> 00:35:23.940
or Ralph Abernathy are up on the
podium do you think they would say

00:35:23.940 --> 00:35:27.410
to the audience who knows
them hi I'm Ralph Abernathy,

00:35:27.410 --> 00:35:28.790
they started talking.

00:35:28.790 --> 00:35:30.510
But who didn't know who they were,

00:35:30.510 --> 00:35:32.740
the white reporters lining
the side of the wall.

00:35:32.740 --> 00:35:34.040
They would lean and say,

00:35:34.040 --> 00:35:36.500
Abe Abernathy how do you
spell that guy's name.

00:35:36.500 --> 00:35:37.800
And so the black reporters

00:35:37.800 --> 00:35:40.900
and the white reporters formed
an alliance in Montgomery.

00:35:40.900 --> 00:35:42.590
Black reporters couldn't
talk to sheriffs,

00:35:42.590 --> 00:35:45.240
they wouldn't give them the time
of day the white reporters could.

00:35:45.240 --> 00:35:46.880
But the black reporters
who were embedded

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:49.320
in the black community could
tell the white reporters what was

00:35:49.320 --> 00:35:50.620
going on.

00:35:50.620 --> 00:35:53.090
So every day at Morton Dean's
Drugstore, I think that's the name

00:35:53.090 --> 00:35:55.490
of it, no it was Dean's
Drugstore not Morton.

00:35:55.490 --> 00:35:57.900
They would meet and
exchange information.

00:35:57.900 --> 00:35:59.290
So here's the little secret bit

00:35:59.290 --> 00:36:01.690
of civil rights reporting
history I love.

00:36:01.690 --> 00:36:04.480
When white liberals in the north
opened up the Washington Post

00:36:04.480 --> 00:36:08.080
and New York Times, the Boston
Globe they were reading coverage

00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:12.060
that was being shaped by
the Negro press of the time,

00:36:12.060 --> 00:36:14.120
the press they didn't
even know existed.

00:36:14.120 --> 00:36:17.510
So even their own coverage was
being shaped by the black press.

00:36:17.510 --> 00:36:20.670
Ethel Payne then did
something quite remarkable.

00:36:20.670 --> 00:36:22.830
She decided that the
black freedom struggle

00:36:22.830 --> 00:36:26.200
in the United States was not merely
a domestic struggle it was tied

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:29.160
intimately to an international
struggle for freedom.

00:36:29.160 --> 00:36:31.030
If you have a map of Africa

00:36:31.030 --> 00:36:35.880
in 1950 all you see are colonies no
black rulers, the same with Asia.

00:36:35.880 --> 00:36:39.980
So there was this remarkable
gathering going on in Bandung,

00:36:39.980 --> 00:36:44.140
Indonesia where folks from all
around the world were coming

00:36:44.140 --> 00:36:47.070 position:56%
to meet together in an international
summit and they were doing

00:36:47.070 --> 00:36:50.970
so without permission and
without inviting the two countries

00:36:50.970 --> 00:36:55.140
that were carving up the world,
the United States and the USSR.

00:36:55.140 --> 00:36:57.690
This was not something
the US was happy about.

00:36:57.690 --> 00:36:59.970
Here's a headline by the way
that gives you a sense of it,

00:36:59.970 --> 00:37:06.030
Afro Asia meet first confab
of world's darker people.

00:37:06.030 --> 00:37:08.640
Adam Clayton Powell said
I'm coming, hang on.

00:37:08.640 --> 00:37:10.510
The State Department
said, no you're not.

00:37:10.510 --> 00:37:12.740
He looked at them and said I'm
an elected member of the House

00:37:12.740 --> 00:37:14.500
of Representatives you don't
tell me where I can go.

00:37:14.500 --> 00:37:17.380
So then they tried tactic number
two, we'll give you a plane

00:37:17.380 --> 00:37:21.040
and a tour of Africa and you can
come back a hero, no thank you.

00:37:21.040 --> 00:37:22.340
So he went.

00:37:22.340 --> 00:37:24.410
Richard Wright abandoned
everything in Paris

00:37:24.410 --> 00:37:26.310
where he was writing a
book and hopped on a plane.

00:37:26.310 --> 00:37:29.670
Everybody who's anybody, including
this wonderful moment in the book

00:37:29.670 --> 00:37:33.310
with Chet Huntley, do you remember
him, the Huntly and Brinkley?

00:37:33.310 --> 00:37:36.630
Just before he became a TV
anchor he was out there.

00:37:36.630 --> 00:37:40.240
And Ethel Payne sent back
her exclusive photographs.

00:37:40.240 --> 00:37:42.080
And a lot of history

00:37:42.080 --> 00:37:46.050 position:56%
of international relations dismissed
the significance of this conference

00:37:46.050 --> 00:37:48.670
because it didn't necessarily
produce anything.

00:37:48.670 --> 00:37:50.270
Well it did produce something,

00:37:50.270 --> 00:37:53.530
it was the first time all the
future leaders who were going

00:37:53.530 --> 00:37:55.840
to liberate their countries
were coming together,

00:37:55.840 --> 00:37:59.770
again without permission, without
approbation, without being part

00:37:59.770 --> 00:38:02.190
of the two countries
carving up the world.

00:38:02.190 --> 00:38:06.240
So the focus began for her
to look elsewhere and outside

00:38:06.240 --> 00:38:08.320
of the United States, as
well as to connect things.

00:38:08.320 --> 00:38:12.420
So in 1957, Ghana became the
first sub-Saharan country

00:38:12.420 --> 00:38:15.440
to become liberated
from colonial rule.

00:38:15.440 --> 00:38:18.840
I should exclude South
Africa and Rhodesia

00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:21.520
and have a black government
take power.

00:38:21.520 --> 00:38:25.590
And so Eisenhower sent Richard
Nixon off to his vice president

00:38:25.590 --> 00:38:27.900
to represent the United
States at the gathering.

00:38:27.900 --> 00:38:33.230
Now this is quite a feat because in
those days Air Force One if we were

00:38:33.230 --> 00:38:36.450
to call the plane that,
getting there is not so easy.

00:38:36.450 --> 00:38:39.010
In fact, one of the planes that
went had to stop in Morocco

00:38:39.010 --> 00:38:40.730
and basically have
its engine replaced.

00:38:40.730 --> 00:38:43.050
So just getting was quite a feat.

00:38:43.050 --> 00:38:46.160
Everybody who was anybody in the
civil rights movement showed up,

00:38:46.160 --> 00:38:47.800
including Martin Luther King.

00:38:47.800 --> 00:38:51.250
This photograph is anachronistic,
it's actually not taken in Ghana,

00:38:51.250 --> 00:38:53.740
but it's the only one I could
find of the two getting together.

00:38:53.740 --> 00:38:56.570
So here's the delicious moment
that Ethel Payne witnesses,

00:38:56.570 --> 00:39:00.080 position:56%
the first time the Martin Luther
King gets to meet the vice president

00:39:00.080 --> 00:39:01.950
of the United States,
not in the United States

00:39:01.950 --> 00:39:04.510
but all the way over in Africa.

00:39:04.510 --> 00:39:06.160
So King says to him, you
know, it's really neat

00:39:06.160 --> 00:39:08.440
to see you here celebrating
black freedom.

00:39:08.440 --> 00:39:11.260
If you really want to see the black
freedom struggle Mr. Vice President

00:39:11.260 --> 00:39:16.220
might you want to come south
and visit us in Alabama,

00:39:16.220 --> 00:39:17.760
Nixon [inaudible] do that?

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:20.160
But why don't you come to
Washington and have a meeting

00:39:20.160 --> 00:39:22.370
with me, which is a big deal.

00:39:22.370 --> 00:39:26.880
So Martin Luther King does come
to Washington subsequently,

00:39:26.880 --> 00:39:29.520
meets with Nixon and then
meets with Eisenhower,

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:33.180
it's the first high level
meetings that occurs.

00:39:33.180 --> 00:39:36.360
Now what was also going
on in 1957 is the debate

00:39:36.360 --> 00:39:38.110
over the 57 Civil Rights Act.

00:39:38.110 --> 00:39:41.320
And the photograph you see up there
you've got Kennedy on the left,

00:39:41.320 --> 00:39:44.930
Hubert Humphrey in the
middle and LBJ on the right.

00:39:44.930 --> 00:39:46.260
You ask any young member

00:39:46.260 --> 00:39:49.020
of our society who's had a
history high school textbook

00:39:49.020 --> 00:39:51.620
and they would immediately
say, oh of course, Kennedy,

00:39:51.620 --> 00:39:54.680
Johnson great heroes of the civil
rights movement, they're the ones

00:39:54.680 --> 00:39:57.040
who kind of got it through right.

00:39:57.040 --> 00:40:01.540
Well, that might be somewhat true
