00:53:03.430 --> 00:53:04.730
&gt;&gt; James McGrath Morris:
You can help me with my.

00:53:04.730 --> 00:53:06.590
&gt;&gt; Yes, he was the
first black reporter

00:53:06.590 --> 00:53:10.500
to lead the White House press
corps Louis [inaudible].

00:53:10.500 --> 00:53:12.690
&gt;&gt; James McGrath Morris: Thank you,
so I was having a long [inaudible].

00:53:12.690 --> 00:53:14.820
Yes, I was having a hard -- I don't
know why, you know, [inaudible].

00:53:14.820 --> 00:53:18.070
And let me tell you about him.

00:53:18.070 --> 00:53:21.260
He's a really nice guy,
but he was uncomfortable

00:53:21.260 --> 00:53:23.470
with Ethel Payne and
Allison Dunnigan.

00:53:23.470 --> 00:53:26.220
He was the one who first complained
that their questions were too long.

00:53:26.220 --> 00:53:30.640
And of course it's 1950's speak,
so he'd write them gals, you know,

00:53:30.640 --> 00:53:32.270
he'd refer to them going on.

00:53:32.270 --> 00:53:35.850
But he was also, he was
like many men who had broken

00:53:35.850 --> 00:53:37.800
through professionally
who was nervous

00:53:37.800 --> 00:53:40.360 position:56%
about his position vis-a-vis whites.

00:53:40.360 --> 00:53:44.070
And so he never was asking
these tough questions

00:53:44.070 --> 00:53:47.150
that if you pardon me
the two gals were asking.

00:53:47.150 --> 00:53:51.260 position:56%
Until finally he says Mr. President,
a lot of people been asking me

00:53:51.260 --> 00:53:54.510
to ask you this question and
I'm sorry, but I have to ask it

00:53:54.510 --> 00:53:56.420
and then he asked a question.

00:53:56.420 --> 00:53:59.360
And I really say that
defensively I'm not attacking him.

00:53:59.360 --> 00:54:02.410
But what was so great for
me going back and looking

00:54:02.410 --> 00:54:05.980
at that world is they're all
three such different people trying

00:54:05.980 --> 00:54:08.970
to navigate the shoals of
racial life in Washington

00:54:08.970 --> 00:54:11.380
and the press corps and
each had a different thing.

00:54:11.380 --> 00:54:21.830 position:56%
People don't understand today when
Ethel Payne and Ray, my mind's gone,

00:54:21.830 --> 00:54:24.220
Mitchell were walking the halls

00:54:24.220 --> 00:54:28.880
of congress not only are they
senators using a word on the floor

00:54:28.880 --> 00:54:31.040
of the house that I would
not repeat in public to refer

00:54:31.040 --> 00:54:33.780
to African-Americans, but
they would brush by them

00:54:33.780 --> 00:54:36.280 position:56%
in the hall as if they didn't exist.

00:54:36.280 --> 00:54:39.550
You know that kind of just knock
into their shoulder slightly.

00:54:39.550 --> 00:54:46.840
So, you know, Louis Lautier was a
male, Ethel Payne had two things

00:54:46.840 --> 00:54:48.990
when she sat in the
back of the press corps,

00:54:48.990 --> 00:54:51.260
she was black and she was female.

00:54:51.260 --> 00:54:55.920
And so when you want to understand
her courage and say Mr. President,

00:54:55.920 --> 00:54:59.410
I first I thought it was her
confronting the great white leader

00:54:59.410 --> 00:55:02.690
of the United States, no there
was something else going on.

00:55:02.690 --> 00:55:07.320
As she said Mr. President hundred
197 male white faces turned around

00:55:07.320 --> 00:55:09.940
and looked at her, all
with the implications

00:55:09.940 --> 00:55:12.520
of where do you get the
chutzpah to ask a question.

00:55:12.520 --> 00:55:14.930
And if I were her I would have
been wearing Depends every day

00:55:14.930 --> 00:55:17.050
that I went into that audience.

00:55:17.050 --> 00:55:18.510
I mean it's a terrifying thing.

00:55:18.510 --> 00:55:21.590
And so I've tried to reconstruct
that because I mean most

00:55:21.590 --> 00:55:23.360
of you obviously know your history.

00:55:23.360 --> 00:55:26.660
But trust me when I talk to
younger audiences they're clueless

00:55:26.660 --> 00:55:29.560
to how daring an act that
was for a black woman

00:55:29.560 --> 00:55:34.040
to challenge the president in
front of 200 other white reporters.

00:55:34.040 --> 00:55:36.400
That was an act of courage.

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:39.000
I guess I can take more questions
and I'm more than one glad

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:41.510
to answer more, I don't
want to keep people here.

00:55:41.510 --> 00:55:50.760
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:55:50.760 --> 00:55:52.560
Yes.

00:55:52.560 --> 00:55:58.060
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:55:58.060 --> 00:56:01.610
Oh yes, including Kathleen
who's right next to you.

00:56:01.610 --> 00:56:04.810
The two things, the sadness
of her self-syndication was

00:56:04.810 --> 00:56:07.100
that she had very little
money, she got social security.

00:56:07.100 --> 00:56:10.230
And I found letters where she was
writing the paper saying, you know,

00:56:10.230 --> 00:56:13.540
you haven't paid me my 50
bucks for those columns.

00:56:13.540 --> 00:56:15.670
And the black press also

00:56:15.670 --> 00:56:18.900
at that point was losing
the power it once had.

00:56:18.900 --> 00:56:22.550
The white press had robbed the
black press of its best reporters.

00:56:22.550 --> 00:56:25.570
And let's think about one of the
reasons the Chicago Defender was

00:56:25.570 --> 00:56:30.240
so successful in 1905 and up to the
50's is that the Chicago Tribune

00:56:30.240 --> 00:56:32.730
and I'm telling it for
Chicago, it could be Baltimore.

00:56:32.730 --> 00:56:35.620
The white press had completely
ignored the black community.

00:56:35.620 --> 00:56:39.630 position:56%
And what do we want to see in
newspapers, high school graduations,

00:56:39.630 --> 00:56:42.100
obituaries, wedding announcements.

00:56:42.100 --> 00:56:44.840
Well once the white
papers began to do

00:56:44.840 --> 00:56:47.350
that it took away a lot
of the economic basis.

00:56:47.350 --> 00:56:50.320
So when she was self-syndicating
those papers didn't have much money

00:56:50.320 --> 00:56:52.580
and didn't have the
same kind of readership.

00:56:52.580 --> 00:56:56.390
I did have a chance to interview
and talk to members of her family,

00:56:56.390 --> 00:56:58.600
including her nephew
who's featured in the book

00:56:58.600 --> 00:57:01.620
who became the first
African-American page

00:57:01.620 --> 00:57:03.910
and was barred from doing that.

00:57:03.910 --> 00:57:07.800
And I'll be glad to tell you
that story later when we're done.

00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:09.350
And I did so for a
number of reasons.

00:57:09.350 --> 00:57:14.190 position:56%
One, I was approaching the story
with enormous trepidation, you know,

00:57:14.190 --> 00:57:16.930
I'm an aging white guy
who am I to write a story

00:57:16.930 --> 00:57:19.410
about a black woman in the 1950's.

00:57:19.410 --> 00:57:21.750
I made a joke at one point
to myself and, you know,

00:57:21.750 --> 00:57:24.080 position:56%
when you make a good joke it's
usually not good for everybody else,

00:57:24.080 --> 00:57:26.080
but I'm walking around the
house laughing up a storm.

00:57:26.080 --> 00:57:29.010
And I said, you know, why
can't a white guy write a story

00:57:29.010 --> 00:57:30.720
about a black woman who
became famous writing

00:57:30.720 --> 00:57:32.020
about a white bald president,

00:57:32.020 --> 00:57:34.200
I actually said a white
kind of white bald guy.

00:57:34.200 --> 00:57:36.650
But anyway and the
truth of the matter was

00:57:36.650 --> 00:57:38.320
that even though I
thought Ethel Payne

00:57:38.320 --> 00:57:41.430
and I if we got together we'd talk
about cooking because we both cook.

00:57:41.430 --> 00:57:43.540
We'd talk about the editors
who messed up our stories.

00:57:43.540 --> 00:57:44.980
We'd have all this shop talk.

00:57:44.980 --> 00:57:49.090
I still was nervous and I wasn't
going to proceed unless those

00:57:49.090 --> 00:57:51.600
who knew her thought I was okay.

00:57:51.600 --> 00:57:55.130
And so it wasn't just interviewing
them it was getting approbation

00:57:55.130 --> 00:57:58.230 position:56%
from those who knew her and then
they could look at my books and say,

00:57:58.230 --> 00:57:59.940
you know, the book
could be very different

00:57:59.940 --> 00:58:03.000
if a young black woman had
written it, but at least it's fair.

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:05.400 position:56%
And then lastly and then I'll answer
your question, then we'll break

00:58:05.400 --> 00:58:09.510
up is that I also discovered
in two of the three places

00:58:09.510 --> 00:58:12.810
that held her papers,
[inaudible], at Howard

00:58:12.810 --> 00:58:16.850 position:56%
and Schaumburg Collection New York
the papers had never been processed,

00:58:16.850 --> 00:58:20.420
25 years after her death they
were still sitting unopened.

00:58:20.420 --> 00:58:22.710
And I thought that was an
invitation, I thought, you know,

00:58:22.710 --> 00:58:26.070 position:56%
I've got the skills as a storyteller
I'm going to go and do this story.

00:58:26.070 --> 00:58:28.210
So those are all the
things that empowered me.

00:58:28.210 --> 00:58:32.510
Quick question then
because you folks.

00:58:32.510 --> 00:58:46.090
[ Inaudible Comment ]

